Hello,
I am writing to respectfully ask for some further information. I have
some questions for you which I hope would not offend someone who has
faith in their beliefs, but would welcome the curiosity of others.
Let me first explain something about myself. I am a 35 year old
married man, with 2 children. I am not a young teen who is struggling
with their own identity. However, I do have some troubling spiritual
questions which I feel that I have never really managed to answer.
Your particular faith seems to positively address some of my own
concerns, e.g. environmentalism, respect and tolerance for others and
a desire to positively influence the world around us. However, after
conducting some research, there are a couple of points that I would
like to address.
I am not expecting you to defend your religion. I simply want some
answers about a faith that I find myself increasingly drawn to. I hope
that, if you answer my questions, that you will not find them
offensive in any way as that is not my intention.
Deities.
Is it your belief that the Goddess and God actually exist as entities,
or are they a symbolic representation or focus for the spirituality
that exists in us all? If they DO exist, why would these &quot;higher
entities&quot; require worship from us? After all, we do not require that
animals (as beings of less highly evolved consciousness?) worship us.
Is it possible that the deities are in fact projections, in the same
way that some people believe that poltergeists are the mental projects
of troubled minds (I am not comparing the nature of poltergeists to
the Goddess and God, simply the source)?
Ritual
Why is there heavy reliance on ritual in Wicca? Does this not take
away from the freedom of individual spirituality, or is it to give it
direction and focus?
Spells
I have heard of spells as being &quot;active prayers&quot;. Do you believe that
these prayers are being answered by another consciousness, or are
simply a tool for influencing our environment for good?  I suppose an
analogy would be our influence of air pressure (via the larynx) for
sound and therefore communication.
What about the idea that Gerald Gardner &quot;invented&quot; Wicca in the
1950's, with the help of Aleister Crowley? Do you feel that this
devalues the religion in any way?
I would also like to know how you feel that Wicca seems to be a
matriarchal belief. Does this not create imbalance, in the same way
that Christianity is a patriarchal belief? Is it not discriminatory?
Thank you for your patience in viewing this,
Regards,
John
